# Event reasons must be specific

Every event written to the database has a `reason` field. This field is what someone reviewing events via the `/events` endpoint actually reads. It must:

- Be a complete sentence
- Include the relevant numbers (the change, the threshold, the actual value)
- Reference both the previous and current values when relevant (temperature swing)

Examples of acceptable reasons:

- `"Temperature rose 6.3°C since previous reading (was 18.1°C, now 24.4°C)"`
- `"10.0 mm of precipitation in the past hour"`
- `"Severe weather reported (WMO code 95)"`

Examples that are not acceptable:

- `"Event detected"`
- `"Temperature changed"`
- `"Weather alert"`

The challenge brief states that every stored event must answer: what happened, in which city, when, and **why this was considered notable**. The `reason` field is the "why" and it carries most of the explanatory weight. When adding a new detector to `app/events.py`, the reason string is part of the design, not an after thought.